rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: The domain or range (or both) of a property (relationships and attributes) is defined by stating more than one rdfs:domain or rdfs:range statements. In OWL multiple rdfs:domain or rdfs:range axioms are allowed, but they are interpreted as conjunction, being, therefore, equivalent to the construct owl:intersectionOf. This pitfall is related to the common error that appears when defining domains and ranges described in [7].
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Defining multiple domains or ranges in properties

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: The domain and range axioms are equal for each of the following object properties. Could they be symmetric or transitive?
rdf:Description.oops:hasCode: SUGGESTION: symmetric or transitive object properties.

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: A class whose name refers to two or more different concepts is created.
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Merging different concepts in the same class

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: Two relationships are defined as inverse relations when they are not necessarily inverse.

An ontology element (a class, an object property or a datatype property) is used in its own definition. Some examples of this would be: (a) the definition of a class as the enumeration of several classes including itself; (b) the appearance of a class within its owl:equivalentClass or rdfs:subClassOf axioms; (c) the appearance of an object property in its rdfs:domain or range rdfs:range definitions; or (d) the appearance of a datatype property in its rdfs:domain definition.

This pitfall consists in creating an ontology element and failing to provide human readable annotations attached to it. Consequently, ontology elements lack annotation properties that label them (e.g. rdfs:label, lemon:LexicalEntry, skos:prefLabel or skos:altLabel) or that define them (e.g. rdfs:comment or dc:description). This pitfall is related to the guidelines provided in [5].

The contents of some annotation properties are swapped or misused. This pitfall might affect annotation properties related to natural language information (for example, annotations for naming such as rdfs:label or for providing descriptions such as rdfs:comment). Other types of annotation could also be affected as temporal, versioning information, among others.
Ontology elements (classes, object properties and datatype properties) are created isolated, with no relation to the rest of the ontology.
Object and/or datatype properties without domain or range (or none of them) are included in the ontology.
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Missing domain or range in properties

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: The ontology lacks information about equivalent properties (owl:equivalentProperty) in the cases of duplicated relationships and/or attributes.
Two classes are defined as equivalent, using owl:equivalentClass, when they are not necessarily equivalent.

This pitfall refers to the creation of a class with the only goal of classifying the instances that do not belong to any of its sibling classes (classes with which the miscellaneous problematic class shares a common direct ancestor).

rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Several classes with the same label
rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: Two or more classes have the same content for natural language annotations for naming, for example the rdfs:label annotation. This pitfall might involve lack of accuracy when defining terms.

rdf:Description.oops:hasAffectedElement: There are elements following different naming conventions as for example: http://www.invincea.com/ontologies/icas/1.0/controls#triggeredResponse http://www.invincea.com/ontologies/icas/1.0/memoryartifacts#FileTable
rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: The ontology elements are not named following the same convention (for example CamelCase or use of delimiters as "-" or "_") . Some notions about naming conventions are provided in [2].
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Using different naming conventions in the ontology

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: This pitfall consists in missing the definition of equivalent classes (owl:equivalentClass) in case of duplicated concepts. When an ontology reuses terms from other ontologies, classes that have the same meaning should be defined as equivalent in order to benefit the interoperability between both ontologies.

This pitfall appears when any relationship (except for those that are defined as symmetric properties using owl:SymmetricProperty) does not have an inverse relationship (owl:inverseOf) defined within the ontology.
